passages.text: F2Q25 Earnings Review: Healthy 2Q beat and FY outlook as greenhools emerge, but tariff uncertainty an overhang
VSC0 12m Price Target: \(18.00 Price:\) 22.67 Downside: \(20.6\%\)

VSC0 posted a healthy 2Q beat amidst muted investor expectations. In the quarter, comps improved sequentially to \(+4.0\%\) Y/Y from \(- 1.0\%\) in 1Q, driven by improvements in both North America stores and digital while international retail comps remained consistent at \(\sim \mathsf{HSD}\%\) . Importantly, comp growth accelerated in July and this momentum has sustained into August MTD. Management spoke to a meaningful inflection in core intimates as a result of strengthening consumer engagement with recent bra launches, supported by stronger marketing and new customer acquisition. Panties growth also inflected to \(+MSD\%\) from - LSD% in 1Q. Beauty and PINK apparel commentary was also constructive. Margins outperformed expectations, driven by lower discounts ( \(\sim 70\) bps), B&O leverage and stronger full price mix, partially offset by gift- with- purchase events ( \(\sim 30\) bps), tariff and freight headwinds ( \(\sim 80\) bps), incremental marketing investments and higher incentives. Net, the company raised its FY sales guidance and maintained its adjusted EPS forecast despite incorporating \(\sim\) 50mn of incremental tariff headwinds.

This was a solid quarter for VSCo, and we step away from the quarter encouraged by the incremental greenhools exhibited across the company's various businesses. In particular, core intimates inflected materially in 2Q. Investments behind recent product launches, marketing, and customer experience are driving healthy new customacquisition, particularly with younger consumers. This suggests that the company's Path to Potential strategy is beginning to take root. That said, we note tariff uncertainty remains a key overhang on the stock and the company is set to navigate tougher compares into 2H25 and 2026.

F2Q Result: VSCO reported ade 2Q EPS of \(\) 0.33\(, ahead of GS/FactSet consensus estimates at\) \ \(0.04 / \Phi 0.13\) . Of the reported basis, revenues increased \(3.0\%\) Y/Y vs. GS/consensus at \(- 1.3\% / - 0.7\%\) , with comps of \(4.0\%\) reported above GS/consensus at \(- 1.2\% /0.0\%\) . Gross margin expanded \(\sim 20\) bps Y/Y to \(35.6\%\) vs. GS/consensus at \(35.1\%\) , and SG&A at \(31.8\%\) of sales was well- controlled vs. GS/consensus at \(33.0\% /32.5\%\) . Net, adj. EBIT margin of \(3.8\%\) was above GS/consensus at \(2.1\% /2.3\%\) .

FY25 Outlook: VSCO maintained its FY25 EPS guidance, expecting adj. EPS of \(\) 1.80-\ \(2.20, which compares to GS/consensus at\) \ \(1.60 / \Phi 1.94\) . Management now expects revenue of \(\) 6.330bn-\ \(6.410bn vs. GS/consensus at\) \ \(6.22bn / \Phi 6.24bn\) and prior guidance of \(\) 6.2- 6.3bn\(. Net, adj. EBIT is still expected at\) \ \(270mn - \Phi 320mn\) which compares to GS/consensus at \(\) 271mn / \Phi 292mn\(. The company also noted its outlook embeds a net tariff impact of\) \sim \ \(100mn\) for the year (vs. \(- \Phi 50mn\) prior). For 3Q, adj. EPS is guided at \(\) 0.55\(to\) \sim \Phi 0.75\(vs. GS/consensus of\) \ \(0.57\) . VSCO expects 3Q revenue of \(\) 1.390bn-\ \(1.420bn (vs. GS/consensus of\) \ \(1.362bn / \Phi 1.357bn\) and adjusted EBIT of \(\) 35mn\(to\) \sim \Phi 55mn\(vs. GS/consensus at\) \sim \Phi 36.5mn / \Phi 40.9mn\$

We update our FY25/FY26/FY27 adjusted EPS estimates to \(\) 1.98/\(\) 2.33/\(\) 3.12\(from\) \ \(1.60 / \Phi 1.91 / \Phi 2.60\) prior to reflect the 2Q beat, stronger momentum in core intimates, lower promotionality, partially offset by incremental marketing investments. We raise our 12- month target price to \(\) 18\(from\) \ \(16\) prior as we roll our Q5- Q8 EV/EBITDA methodology forward, now based on a 4.2x target multiple (vs. 4x prior) to reflect a stronger growth outlook driven by emerging greenhооts across the business. Key upside risks include (1) a resurgence in brand momentum, including at the PINK brand, (2) strategic initiatives prove to be more impactful than anticipated, and (3) an inflection in overall intimate market trends. We are Sell rated.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
